The Lighthouse That Collected Storms
Old Mira kept the lighthouse on Widow's Point for forty years, and in that time she'd started collecting something odd: storms.
Not real ones — bottled ones. Each time a storm rolled in, she'd catch a jar of rain, a swirl of wind, a flash of lightning trapped in glass, and shelve it in the lighthouse tower. Sailors thought she was mad. Children thought she was magic.
One October night, a boy named Sam rowed out during the worst storm in a decade, chasing a runaway dog. His boat capsized. Mira saw him from the tower, grabbed her oldest jar — the storm from the night her husband died at sea — and hurled it into the waves.
The bottled storm exploded outward, pushing back the real one just long enough. Sam grabbed a plank and floated safely to shore.
The next morning, the sea was calm as glass. Mira's shelf had one empty space, but she didn't mind.
"Some storms," she told Sam, "are meant to be saved for exactly one moment."
She never explained what she meant. But every October after that, Sam brought her a new jar, empty, waiting to be filled.
